[section className:"article-body"]

A *Quest* [a href:"https://www.minervaquest.com/2020/10/10/shipping-financial-aid-packages-from-a-us-based-university-to-a-global-student-body/" target:"_blank"] report[/a] on the state of financial aid at Minerva details how changeing currency rates have negatively affected students' ability to pay for Minerva tuition fees in two ways:

* **Long-term currency devaluation** - A currency that continuously [div class:"tooltip"]weakens[span class:"tooltiptext"][b]Weakening[/b] of a currency, or [b]devaluation/depreciation[/b], means that the value of that currency decreases relative to other currencies. For instance, if one can buy $1 USD with $1 Minerva Dollars yesterday, but only $0.90 USD with $1 Minerva Dollar today, the Minerva Dollar has depreciated against the USD by 10% [/span][/div] against the USD effectively raises tuition costs for students who purchase USD from their home currency to pay tuition fees. This type of devaluation hits students whose families have saved their home currency to pay Minerva tuition particularly hard as the value of their savings depreciates proportional to the weakening of their currency. 

* **Short-term currency fluctuations** - Financial aid packages are released in March, whereas term bill payments are due in July and November for the fall and spring semesters respectively. If a currency's value changes in the months between these dates and if a student pays for the term bill in that currency by [div class:"tooltip"]purchasing USD[span class:"tooltiptext"] If you and your family don't have USD on hand, paying for the term bill in your home currency means that you're [b]purchasing USD[/b] because Minerva doesn't accept payment in your currency![/span][/div], their expected family contribution changes proportionally with the change in their currency's value. 

[hr /]

Members of the Minerva community have likely heard of anecdots of students struggling with tuition fees because of changing forex rates. This Quest report investigates how changing rates affects different students quantitatively having gathered the forex rates data from 2017 to 2020 for the 65 currencies used in countries where at least one Minerva student identifies as their country of origin [div class:"tooltip"]except Zimbabwe & Venezuela[span class:"tooltiptext"] [b]Zimbabwe[/b] started to use a new [b]Zimbabwe[/b] Dollar in 2019, while the [b]Venezuelan[/b] Fuerte was replaced by the [b]Venezuelan[/b] Bolívar in 2018. Changes in their currency systems disallow comparisons between forex rates from 2017 to 2020[/span][/div].


**Which students pay more and pay less because of their home currency? And by roughly how much or little?**
[br /]
[br /]


[div className:'hed']Long-term Currency Devaluation[/div]
[br /]
Giovanna Chaves (M'20), [a href:"https://www.minervaquest.com/2020/10/10/shipping-financial-aid-packages-from-a-us-based-university-to-a-global-student-body/" target:"_blank"] told[/a] *the Quest* that because of currency devaluation in Brazil, her home country, her first-year term bill from 2016 would cost almost twice as many Brazilian Reals if she had to pay it in 2020. Many students would be financially ruined if their school fees rose so dramatically, but this is the reality for those from countries that use currencies that have consistently weakened against the USD. 

