[section className:"article-body"]
[div className:'hed']Short-term Currency Fluctuations[/div]
Minerva's current financial aid system does not account for short term currency fluctuations that could put students in a difficult financial position. Financial aid packages are released in March, whereas term bill payments are due in July and November for the fall and spring semesters. The value of some particularly volatile currencies could change drastically in the time between these dates, to the point that the family contribution outlined in a financial aid package might be an entirely different amount of money by the time payments are due. Between March 2020 and November 2020, the Argentine Peso and Turkish Lira depreciated significantly, which led to a price increase of Argentine and Turkish students' fees by 29% and 21% respectively. 

[/section]

[FullWidth]
  [Flourish visualisation:"5006590" /]
[/FullWidth]

[section className:"article-body"]
One of the financial aid [a href:"https://www.minervaquest.com/2020/10/10/shipping-financial-aid-packages-from-a-us-based-university-to-a-global-student-body/" target:"_blank"] Day of Action [/a] demands was that students receive "an expected family contribution in both USD and the student's home currency" in their financial aid packages. Such a policy would [div class:"tooltip"]shield [span class:"tooltiptext"] If a student's currency weakened between March and November, they wouldn't have to pay more because they would pay with the forex rate in March instead of the forex rate in November. In contrast, those with stronger currencies wouldn't get to pay less by taking advantage of their relatively stronger currency. [/span][/div] students from currency fluctuations. The Minerva senior team [a href:"https://d1c2gz5q23tkk0.cloudfront.net/assets/uploads/2924499/asset/Minerva_Response_to_Student_Demands_-_April_16_2020_%281%29.pdf?1587058414" target:"_blank"]concluded[/a] that they "cannot assume all of the risk and shield students and parents entirely from currency fluctuations as this would make financial planning and budgeting unduly hard and more expensive." 

Some students have resorted to unorthodox strategies to reduce their financial burden. A South African student told *the Quest* that she had used Minerva's payment plan option to pay term bills in installments to wait out a period of poor forex rates, hoping that the South African Rand would appreciating against the USD within half a year. 

For instance, the term bill for the Fall20 semester was due on 15th July 2020. The payment plan would divide a student's payment into three installments due on 15th July 2020, 15th September 2020, and 15th November 2020. If a student's home currency appreciates between these dates, then a student might be able to save on their term bill. 
[/section]

