[section className:"article-body"]
However, a [div class:"tooltip"]service fee[span class:"tooltiptext"] For example, a payment plan on a term bill of [b]$30,000 USD[/b] would end up costing the student [b]$31,200 USD[/b], ignoring any changes in currency exchange rates. [/span][/div] of 4% of the term bill is charged to the student should they choose to use a payment plan.  Additionally, opting for a payment plan runs the additional risk that if one's home currency depreciates even more, each installment becomes more and more expensive in the home currency. [div class:"tooltip"]Backtesting[span class:"tooltiptext"] Backtesting results are included in the methodological notes are at the bottom of this article! [/span][/div] a payment plan strategy for the Fall20 billing period reveals that only this strategy would have resulted in a cheaper bill for students whose home currency is the Mexican Peso. **The installment strategy is not only a dangerous gamble but one that is highly unlikely to succeed.** 

Of course, students would prefer a payment plan for a variety of different reasons. If a student's home currency is weak and short of USD when the term bill is due but has a source of income in the United States, it might be worth the 4% fee to service installments with their USD earnings rather than purchase USD using their home currency. A finding that surfaced after digging into the viability of a payment plan strategy is that **students who earn their school fees in increasingly weak home currencies should generally [div class:"tooltip"]avoid[span class:"tooltiptext"] Delaying payments progressively increases each installment cost for those with weak home currencies since their currency will be worth less when the next installment is due, compared to paying the entire term bill at the deadline. [/span][/div] taking a payment plan.** 

[/section]

[section className:"article-body"]
[div className:'hed']Main Takeaways[/div]

* Long term currency devaluation significantly increases Minerva fees for students with consistently weakening home currencies. Students who anticipate further weakening of their home currency should try to purchase USD for term bills payments earlier if possible.
* Lower-income students who do not hold savings in USD from countries with weak home currencies will most likely have to find a job in the United States to service student debt.
* Using installment payment plans to wait for short term home currency appreciation against the USD is not viable given the risk of further currency depreciation and a 4% payment plan service fee.
* Students considering Minerva's payment plan, those who anticipate further weakening of their home currency should avoid opting for installment if they plan to use earnings in their home currency to service installments, but could consider doing so if they earn in USD.
[hr/]
These takeaways are likely common knowledge among students who are negatively affected by forex rates. **A thorough understanding of forex rates is crucial for all students to make informed financial decisions regarding the cost of their Minerva education.**

*When should I purchase USD to pay for the next term bill? Should I try to aim for a summer job at home or in the United States? Should I take on these student loans if I want to work a job at home after graduation?* 

Understanding how forex affects one's financial standing can support students financial aid appeals should they find the family contribution in their financial aid packages impossible to afford. According to Niko Pelka, Minerva's Chief Finance Officer, large currency swings over the past 12 months are one factor that Minerva's financial aid system considers in assessing financial aid applications. Are there some potential targeted interventions that could benefit the most negatively affected students?

Currency volatility data reveals that only a minority of currencies have their value [div class:"tooltip"]fixed[span class:"tooltiptext"] A [b]fixed[/b] exchange rate is a regime applied by a government or central bank that ties the country's official currency exchange rate to another country's currency. The purpose of a fixed exchange rate system is to keep a currency's value stable. [/span][/div] to the USD. Thus, forex rates affect most non-American students at Minerva, although it is clear that students are affected by varying degrees. As with many problematic issues facing the Minerva student community, the systemic consequencies and dynamics of global inequalities affect some students more than others. 
[/section]

