[section className:"article-body"]

Students with home [div class:"tooltip"]currencies[span class:"tooltiptext"] Examples include the United Arab Emirates Dirham, Jordanian Dinar, and the Hong Kong Dollar. [/span][/div] that maintain a fixed exchange rate with the USD are not affected at all. On the other hand, the most volatile [div class:"tooltip"]currencies[span class:"tooltiptext"] Examples include Argentine Peso, Uzbekistan Som, and the Turkish Lira. [/span][/div] are usually the same currencies that depreciate the most against the USD compared to other currencies. 

It is also important to note that students who use the same currency are not necessarily affected in the same way, as Minerva students come from a diverse range of socio-economic backgrounds. A limitation of this investigation is that the data is only performed at a currency-level. This currency-level analysis neglects an individual's socio-economic context about these forex shifts, which is imperative for the Minerva community to truly understand how these forex shifts can negatively or positively affect individuals. 

**Widespread acknowledgement and understanding of how forex rates impacts individual students and their communities can help the Minerva students lobby for improvements in the Minerva financial aid system.**
